# Conventions — {{project_name}}

> One hop from `AGENTS.md`, which wins on any conflict. Elaboration and
> worked examples only — the binding rules live there.

## Debugging

- Every entry point (CLI, server, test target, frontend page) gets a
  `.vscode/launch.json` profile (or your IDE's equivalent) when it is
  created, so the next debugger doesn't reverse-engineer it.
- Canonical hosts, ports, and env vars live in README §Debug. Check
  there before attaching; add what's missing — don't guess or hardcode.
- Frontend local-file access during debug: temporarily expand
  `vite.config.*` `server.fs.allow` (or the equivalent) and drive
  uploads from in-page JS — native file dialogs break headless and
  DevTools-driven debugging. Revoke the expansion when the session ends.

## Communication examples

- "Per D-073 we capped X" → "Per D-073 (the retry-budget cap) we capped
  X" — the reader doesn't have the decision log memorized.
- "We switched to RPC" → "We switched the inter-process call layer to
  RPC (HTTP+JSON over a local socket)"; the short form is fine after.
- "Performance is better" → "p50 dropped from 240ms to 90ms on the smoke
  task" — show the difference, don't adjective it.
- When pasting code, inline-comment any variable whose meaning isn't
  self-evident inside the snippet; the reader lacks your file context.
- If you'd have to look a phrase up in six months, rewrite it now.

## Alias mechanics

Alias files in the repo root (`CLAUDE.md`, `GEMINI.md`, legacy
`AGENT.md`) are either symlinks with the relative target `AGENTS.md`
(same directory, never an absolute path) or one-line pointer files
containing exactly `@AGENTS.md` — the import syntax Claude Code and
Gemini CLI resolve mechanically. A legacy bare `AGENTS.md` line is also
treated as a pointer. Tools that read `AGENTS.md` directly (Codex CLI,
Cursor) need no alias; tools with neither auto-discovery nor import
syntax are bridged by a symlink or by their own config pointed at
`AGENTS.md`. Duplicating content across alias files is the failure
mode this pattern exists to prevent.

## Paths and state

- Repo-internal references stay relative so the docs survive a clone to
  any machine; `${PROJECT_ROOT}` indirection also works.
- Genuinely environment-bound references (another local repo, a system
  service, a tool install location) carry a `(local-env)` tag so readers
  know the line will not travel.
- `.agent_works/` is committed durable state; the dot-prefix signals
  "meta, not code" (IDE file trees hide it by default). `.local/` is
  gitignored session scratch.
- Local model weights go in `models/` (gitignored) with a download
  script and setup notes in README.

## README vs AGENTS.md

`README.md` is the human's entry point — optimize it for clone-and-run
in ~5 minutes: what the project is, install, configure, run, verify, and
the debug addresses / ports. `AGENTS.md` is the agent's entry point —
routing, rules, working principles. Same project, two audiences, no
content overlap. For README craft, browse the curated examples at
<https://github.com/matiassingers/awesome-readme>.
